	<td bgcolor="#666699" width="100%" valign="top">
	
	<!-- Main Post Body -->
	<table width="100%" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" border="0">
	<td bgcolor="#4D4D73"><img src="images/posticon.gif" border="0" alt="Old Post"></td><td width="100%" bgcolor="#4D4D73"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF">
	Posted 12-11-2003 <font color="#FEDE01">03:27 PM</font></font></td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">Welcome to the conversation Varyx.  I'd be glad to address your points, one by one.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">Argument: The sale of platinum is directly responsible for platinum cheats and hacks.<br />
<br />
This is obviously false. As mentioned (ironically in a post against selling platinum) other games exist that have no economy and no translation to American dollars. In these games (for example, Half-Life) cheats are rampant. I would go so far as to say they are on some order of magnitude more abundant than in EverQuest.<br />
<br />
We already know for a fact that people value EverQuest platinum as highly as they do the American dollar, at a certain ratio. Therefore, platinum must hold some intrinsic value to buyers (i.e. there would be no market if everyone was buying platinum with the future intention of converting it back to American dollars). People are willing to steal American dollars, it is therefore reasonable to conclude that people are willing to steal (hack, cheat) EverQuest platinum, regardless of relation to American dollars.<br />
<br />
Getting rid of the sale of platinum to American dollars will not halt the flow of cheats and hacks into EverQuest. I doubt it will even slow it.<br />
</td></tr></table><br />
<br />
The post you reference is my post.  The point you make is simply contraindicated by reality.  Cheater motivation in Half-life was usually motivated by one of two things.  Desire for fun, or desire for apparent skill.  Cheating in EQ is motivated by those two things AND the desire for money.<br />
<br />
Cheating in games where no real money is on the line, and the basis is not subscriptive runs rampant for the very simple reason that there is no incentive to stop it.  EQ has a player base to maintain.  Half-Life and Diablo 2 had *already* made their money by the initial sale of the box.  Therefore, EQ has more at stake, and slows cheating.<br />
<br />
I submit that if SOE did as only as much as Valve or Blizzard to stop hacks or cheats, then you'd have rampant cheating in EQ.  As it is, it's *hard* to cheat in EQ.  And because it is hard, the you need more motivation to go out and do it.  While I won't compare the relative situation of fun and desire, the addition of making money in the game is unlikely to *slow* the use of cheats and hacks.<br />
<br />
Furthermore, you argue, once again, that if people making $$$ didn't do it, someone else would.  This is a morally flawed argument.  If you shoot your wife, and then tell the courts that if you hadn't shot her, her father would have that night, then you're still guilty.  If you steal a pack of gum, and tell the courts that another kid was about to steal that pack of gum, you're still guilty. <br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;"><br />
Argument: Buying and selling platinum hurts the EverQuest economy.<br />
<br />
How? In the arguments against buying and selling platinum, this is somehow taken as a given rather than a point that needs to be proven. If this holds true, then gifts of platinum would also be detrimental to the economy. We would have to argue that giving 5k to a friend to help him buy a horse is wrong. I doubt anyone here would be willing to argue that.<br />
<br />
In fact, the purchase of platinum ultimately reintroduces saved coin back into the economy. I know several high end players that are sitting on hundreds of thousands of platinum with no intention of doing anything with it. All their gear is nodrop, they own the highest end horse... what could they reasonably do with their platinum? Giving their platinum to a middleman who would distribute to players willing to spend that platinum would simply reintroduce coin into the economy that belongs in that economy. The fact that American dollars are exchanged and that the middleman is making real profit is irrelevant to the EverQuest economy. Certainly no one would fault a high end player going into the bazaar and giving away his money on a first come, first serve basis... why when American dollars are added to the equation is this suddenly an offense of morality?<br />
</td></tr></table><br />
<br />
There are several subpoints here.<br />
<br />
1) Selling platinum is no different than giving a gift of platinum.<br />
<br />
No one would argue that giving a friend 5k, or a random joe 5k, to buy his horse is wrong.  However, introducing money into the equation can, and is, a fair judgement of whether an activity is ethical or harmful to an economy.  <br />
<br />
If you give a friend 5k, because you like him, or you have no use for the 5k, that's one thing.  However, when you sell 50k to Yantis, for $45 to fix your dishwasher, or feed your starving somalian children, or whatever, you are giving it to him because what he gives you back is worth more in return.  Therefore, it creates a reason for you to generate more money than you need for the game, or all your friends, or even everyone you've ever grouped with.  Because while you'd get sick and tired of farming a 250kpp item if all you were gonna do is give out 5k to every newbie in Gfaydark, you will not stop doing the same farming, exploit, cheat, hack, or even simple honest money making if that 250kpp is going to be half your rent check for the month.<br />
<br />
Selling platinum makes platinum valuable much higher quantities than the game mechanics do.  Thus, more platinum is introduced into the economy.<br />
<br />
2) Selling platinum reintroduces coin into the economy, which is a good thing.<br />
<br />
This is a *very* complicated economic principal, which I am not fully equipped to address.  But I can say one thing to this statement.  <br />
<br />
While it is not inherently false, it is likely, that on the majority of EQ servers, the economy is one of consistent deflation.  Consistently deflated economies DO NOT need more currency.  <br />
<br />
They need less.  Less of something is more valuable.  The less valuable platinum becomes, the more out of reach items traded between players become to those who are not already rich, and are not participating in the illegal or unethical methods of platinum gathering.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">Argument: Buying platinum leads to a less skilled playerbase.</td></tr></table><br />
<br />
I agree with you here.  Buying platinum does not affect the level of skill you have.  It could, ab reductum absurdo, have an effect on the playerbase as a whole, but I don't think it's a significant effect of the platinum trade.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">Argument: Buying and selling platinum is a breach of the EULA and therefore wrong.<br />
<br />
This has been brought up, but the exchange of platinum has, for a while now, been seen as an exchange of time. When you buy 50k, you're buying the time required to farm it up, not the platinum itself. The platinum is just an expression of that time. It's a loophole. Of course, the consequence of closing this loophole, which however done would implicitly grant SOE ownership of your *time*, is unacceptable (I think this is a given).</td></tr></table><br />
<br />
Exchange of time arguments are fallacious from their outset.  Imagine this:  I work for an engineering company.  While I work for this engineering company, I specifically sign a document that says any innovation I make that is patentable becomes their intellectual property, as long as it is relevant to their business.   I spend time at home sitting and thinking up an innovation, and then go sell it to a competitor or an outside party, without their consent.  They sue me, and I defend myself by saying "Hah!  I didn't sell their innovation.  I sold the time I invested in making that innovation!"<br />
<br />
The argument may be a legal loophole, but legal loopholes have very little to do with definitions of right and wrong.  <br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">Argument: The "laissez-faire" attitude is ruining the game.</td></tr></table><br />
<br />
I don't believe I said quite that it was ruining the game.  If I did, i should be more specific.  I meant that it is ruining the game economy. <br />
<br />
But here again, as you make your point, I agree in most ways.  As long as the game is fun, I don't care.<br />
<br />
<table border="0" align="center" width="90%" cellpadding="3" cellspacing="1"><tr><td><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" color="#FFFFFF"><b>quote:</b></font></td></tr><tr><td style="BORDER: #000000 1px solid; FONT-SIZE: 11px; COLOR: #FFFFFF; FONT-FAMILY: Verdana,Arial; BACKGROUND-COLOR: #4D4D73;">It seems to me like the people most adamant against the purchase of platinum are themselves the ones that care more about loot and plat than in enjoying the game.</td></tr></table><br />
<br />
And it seems to me that you went to great length to defend a practice that you do not care about.  But, more on the point, you're wrong, I care a great deal more about enjoying the game than about loot.  I probably spent 2 hours posting on this topic, all told.<br />
<br />
But I've spent countless hours enjoying EQ and making friends.  I don't have a horse, I've never touched a flowing thought item, and my best gear is all gifts from my wonderful family guild.  So saying I am a greedy loot-lover is a bit of a low blow.</font></p>
	
	<p><p><img src="/forums/images/sig_separator.gif" width="282" height="11" Alt="Hey! Watch where you point that thing!"><br>
