	<tr><td colspan="2" bgcolor="#666699" vAlign="TOP">
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">I agree with pretty much everything Moonsorrow has been saying.<br />
<br />
One thing I will comment on is the comments regarding Laissez Faire. Letting businessmen do whatever they want doesn't work. This was the prevailing thought toward the beginning of the 20th century in the U.S., and it led to tycoons that over-worked and under-paid their employees. There were countless shysters hawking magic potions, and horribly ill-produced products from "legitimate" businesses...notably the food industry. I know there are probably some Adam Smiths out there, but I disagree horribly with letting business do its own just in principle. How you apply this argument to EQ is up to you, but there needs to be some measure of control.<br />
<br />
At the very least, the issue of counterfeiting money (i.e. plat duping) should be squished on very hard, and has been addressed as of late. There are still plat sweatshops out there though, where people have a non-stop crew farming guard in Seb at some pittance wages. I don't want to know exactly how Yantis sub-licenses his clients' orders, but I'm sure he isn't sitting on Stormhammer leveling all these characters himself.<br />
<br />
More to the point, Everquest is a game, not a job. The only people who should be earning money from it are the people who are responsible for creating and administering it. I'll extend this to people who offer a legitimate service like Allakhazam, who I put on the level of, with it being far less of a waste of money, Prima's so-called strategy guides.</font></p>
	
	<p><p><img src="/forums/images/sig_separator.gif" width="282" height="11" Alt="Hey! Watch where you point that thing!"><br>
<font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" color="#FFFFFF">

Only the exceptions can be exceptional.<br />
<br />
Friends don't let friends do tradeskills. (tm)
</font></p></p>
	<p></p>
